📘 Subject: General Studies Paper I (Prelims – Polity)
🧠 Topic: Citizenship in India

(Very important topic for Prelims. Questions frequently asked.)

1️⃣ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
🔹 Meaning of Citizenship

Citizenship refers to the legal relationship between an individual and the state.

A citizen enjoys:

Political rights

Civil rights

Legal protection

Example rights only for citizens:

Voting

Contesting elections

Public employment

🔵 Constitutional Provisions

Citizenship is covered under:

📖 Articles 5 to 11 of the Constitution.

However, the Constitution does not permanently define citizenship.

It empowers Parliament to make laws.

🔹 Citizenship at the Commencement of Constitution

At the start of the Constitution (1950), citizenship was granted to people who:

1️⃣ Were born in India
2️⃣ Had parents born in India
3️⃣ Had lived in India for at least 5 years

🔴 Citizenship Act, 1955

This Act provides methods of acquiring and losing citizenship.

🔹 Ways of Acquiring Citizenship

1️⃣ By Birth
2️⃣ By Descent
3️⃣ By Registration
4️⃣ By Naturalization
5️⃣ By Incorporation of Territory

📌 Very common UPSC question.

🔹 Loss of Citizenship

A person can lose citizenship by:

1️⃣ Renunciation – voluntarily giving it up
2️⃣ Termination – acquiring foreign citizenship
3️⃣ Deprivation – government cancels citizenship

🔹 Single Citizenship

India follows single citizenship unlike federal countries like USA.

Meaning:

Only Indian citizenship

No state citizenship

🔹 Important Amendments
Citizenship Amendment Act (CAA) 2019

Provides citizenship to certain migrants from:

Pakistan

Bangladesh

Afghanistan

For specific religious communities.

📌 Highly debated policy.

